1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,000
A flash flood cuts off two neighborhoods.

2
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,000
One temporary bridge brings 284 households back online.

3
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:21,000
Lifeline is a rehearsal tool for flood-access planning.

4
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Instead of pretending to predict the future, it lets a municipal team test one intervention, watch the network change, and see who regains critical access to shelter and care first.

5
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:39,285
We start in Riverbend East.

6
00:00:39,285 --> 00:00:48,571
The district is compact, but it has one fragile link: the east crossing.

7
00:00:48,571 --> 00:00:57,857
As soon as the severe flash flood scenario is applied, access drops from six hundred and twelve households to three hundred and twenty eight.

8
00:00:57,857 --> 00:01:07,142
Two east-side clusters lose reachable paths to both the shelter and the clinic.

9
00:01:07,142 --> 00:01:16,428
And what I like here is that the app makes the failure legible fast.

10
00:01:16,428 --> 00:01:25,714
You can click the isolated clusters, inspect the side panel, and see that this is not just a red map.

11
00:01:25,714 --> 00:01:35,000
It is a concrete service-access problem.

12
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:42,000
Here’s the cool part.

13
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:49,000
Instead of making the team guess, Lifeline lets them arm a single deployable action and place it exactly where it matters.

14
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:56,000
In this case, a temporary bridge at East Crossing.

15
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:03,000
The board reruns immediately, the metric strip jumps back up, and both isolated clusters reconnect.

16
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:10,000
That is the payoff: one action, visible network recovery, and a quantified result.

17
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:21,250
And the app does not stop at a visual result.

18
00:02:21,250 --> 00:02:32,500
The run can be saved immediately.

19
00:02:32,500 --> 00:02:43,750
That lands on a detailed report with the board snapshot, baseline versus flooded versus resolved metrics, the generated narrative, editable notes, and exportable JSON.

20
00:02:43,750 --> 00:02:55,000
So this becomes something a team can reference later, compare against other rehearsals, or hand to someone who never touched the board in the first place.

21
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:05,000
That saved run also turns into a public replay.

22
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:15,000
So the output can travel outside the workspace as a clean, read-only artifact.

23
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:25,000
The result stays understandable, the timeline stays visible, and nobody needs a planner account just to understand what happened.

24
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:35,000
For a hackathon demo, this is a big deal, because the proof does not disappear when the person driving the app stops talking.

25
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:44,000
Once a team has more than one rehearsal, the product starts to feel more operational.

26
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:53,000
Analytics shows run volume over time and which interventions are actually getting used.

27
00:03:53,000 --> 00:04:02,000
Settings and the recent activity feed show that this is built for a team environment, not just a solo simulation toy.

28
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:11,000
In other words, the value compounds.

29
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:20,000
Every run adds context, every run is auditable, and the organization can start to build a playbook instead of one-off screenshots.

30
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:25,000
Under the hood, this is a deterministic network simulation.

31
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:30,000
A scenario changes edge states from normal to degraded or blocked.

32
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:35,000
An intervention adds or restores a path at a valid anchor.

33
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:40,000
Then the app recalculates access cluster by cluster against the shelter and clinic thresholds.

34
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:45,000
That is why the story feels credible.

35
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:50,000
The visuals are clean, but the numbers are grounded in an explicit model.

36
00:04:50,000 --> 00:05:05,000
For a team planning under pressure, that means faster rehearsal, clearer tradeoffs, and a result they can actually share.
